review_2.column_1_text:
The size of angle PQR equals angle SQT as they are vertically opposite angles.

Using the protractor, the size of angle PQR is 60°.

This means angle SQT measures 60°.

Tip

Vertically opposite angles are equal.

success.question_text:
What is the length of AE?

Type the number of centimetres in the box, e.g. for 2 cm type 2.
success.question_hint:
• A side of length 45 cm has reduced to 30 cm in the reduction.
  • This is a ratio of 3:2 so apply this same reduction for a side of 30 cm.

stimulus_1.text: ABCD is a rectangle with AB = 45 cm and BC = 30 cm. ABCD is reduced to AGFE, with AG = BC.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Shapes are enlarged or reduced by a certain multiple, the enlargement (or reduction) factor. If the factor is greater than 1, the shape is enlarged. If the factor is less than 1 the shape is reduced.

success.question_hint:
• x° and 100° are the angles that make up a straight line.
  • There is 180° in a straight angle.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Angles in a straight line add to 180°. Take care that only the angles that together make the straight line actually add to 180°. For example, in this question the angle of 45° has no effect on the size of x.

success.question_text:
‘In any                                    , the                            sides are equal.’

Which two words can replace the spaces in the above statement and create a true statement?
success.question_hint:
• A quadrilateral is any four-sided shape where the sides may or may not be the same length.
  • The question says ‘In any …’ so it is meaning ‘All …’.

review_2.column_1_text:
Try each option:

  • ‘In any quadrilateral, the adjacent sides are equal.’
    This is not true. Many quadrilaterals have no equal sides.
  • ‘In any quadrilateral, the opposite sides are equal.’
    This is also not true.
  • ‘In any parallelogram, the adjacent sides are equal.’
    This is not true. In some parallelograms the adjacent sides are equal but only when the parallelogram is also a rhombus.
  • ‘In any parallelogram, the opposite sides are equal.’ This statement is correct.

The words that will make the statement true are ‘parallelogram’ and ‘opposite’.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Any four-sided plane figure is a quadrilateral. If the quadrilateral has two pairs of opposite sides parallel, it is a parallelogram.

success.question_hint:
• Look at the bottom of the flagpole and rotate the top of the flag a quarter turn in a clockwise direction.
  • Now reflect over the vertical line.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Under a reflection, every part of the image should be the same distance from the line of reflection as the corresponding part of the original object.

success.question_hint:
• The angles in a triangle add to 180°.
  • It is an isosceles triangle so the two bottom angles must be the same size.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

An isosceles triangle has two equal sides and two equal angles. The angles opposite the equal sides are equal.

success.question_hint:

review_5.column_1_text:
Tip

There are often many lines perpendicular to a given line. For example, in this question AE, AH, AD, BC, BG and BF are all perpendicular to AB.

success.question_text:
‘Compared to a triangular pyramid, a triangular prism has …’

Which could correctly complete this statement?
success.question_hint:
• Count the faces, edges and vertices of both solids.
  • Compare the characteristics of the prism to the pyramid.

review_3.column_1_text:
A triangular pyramid has four faces, six edges and four vertices.

A triangular prism has five faces, nine edges and six vertices.

So, compared to a triangular pyramid, a triangular prism has one more face, two more vertices and three more edges.

Tip

For any solid the number of faces plus the number of vertices is always two more than the number of edges. This is Euler’s rule.

choice_1.label: one more face, two more edges and three more vertices.

choice_2.label: one more face, two more vertices and three more edges.

choice_3.label: one more vertex, two more faces and three more edges.

choice_4.label: one more vertex, two more edges and three more faces.

success.question_hint:
• Use Pythagoras’ theorem to find the missing sides of the triangles.
  • Similar triangles will have matching sides in the same ratio.

review_5.column_1_text:
Tip

Similar figures are the same shape but not necessarily the same size. The corresponding angles of similar figures are equal. The corresponding sides of similar figures are in proportion.
